{"title_page": "2009 Connecticut vs. Syracuse men's basketball game", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball game}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NCAABasketballSingleGame\n| Name               = 2009 Connecticut vs. Syracuse<br>\"6-overtime game\"\n| Type               = Big East Tournament Quarterfinals\n| Image              = \n| Date               = March 12, 2009\n| Year               = 2008\u201309\n| Visitor School     = Syracuse University\n| Visitor Name Short = Syracuse\n| Visitor Nickname   = Orange\n| Visitor Record     = 24\u20138\n| Visitor AP         = 18\n| Visitor Coaches    = 20\n| Visitor Coach      = [[Jim Boeheim]]\n| Visitor1           = 34\n| Visitor2           = 37\n| VisitorOT1         = 10\n| VisitorOT2         = 6\n| VisitorOT3         = 11\n| VisitorOT4         = 6\n| VisitorOT5         = 6\n| VisitorOT6         = 17\n| Home School        = University of Connecticut\n| Home Name Short    = Connecticut\n| Home Nickname      = Huskies\n| Home Record        = 27\u20133\n| Home AP            = 3\n| Home Coaches       = 4\n| Home Coach         = [[Jim Calhoun]]\n| Home1              = 37\n| Home2              = 34\n| HomeOT1            = 10\n| HomeOT2            = 6\n| HomeOT3            = 11\n| HomeOT4            = 6\n| HomeOT5            = 6\n| HomeOT6            = 7\n| Arena              = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n| City               = [[Manhattan|New York, New York]]\n| Attendance         = 19,375\n| US Network         = [[College Basketball on ESPN|ESPN]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Sean McDonough]], [[Bill Raftery]] and [[Jay Bilas]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2009 Connecticut vs. Syracuse men's basketball game''' was a quarterfinal game of the [[2009 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]] between the No. 18 [[2008\u201309 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse Orange]] (No. 6 seed in Big East Tournament) and No. 3 [[2008\u201309 Connecticut Huskies men's basketball team|Connecticut (UConn) Huskies]]. The 2009 UConn\u2013Syracuse basketball game took place on Thursday, March 12, 2009 at [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City]], more specifically in [[Manhattan]].\n\nThis quarterfinal game of the 2009 Big East Tournament went to six overtimes, resulting in a 127\u2013117 Syracuse victory. The Orange won the game without leading at any time during the first five overtimes. The game began at 9:36{{nbsp}}p.m. and ended at 1:22{{nbsp}}a.m. on March 13, 2009, spanning 3 hours and 46 minutes. During the game, 244 total points were scored (102 scored during overtime), 211 field goals were attempted (103 attempted in overtime), 93 free throws were attempted, 66 fouls were committed, and eight total players fouled out (four from each team).\n\nThis game was the second-longest in college basketball history and the longest in Big East history. The longest game in college basketball history was the 1981 [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]] vs. [[Bradley Braves men's basketball|Bradley]] game in which [[1981 Bradley vs. Cincinnati men's basketball game|Cincinnati beat Bradley 75\u201373 on December 21, 1981]]. That game took place before the implementation of the [[shot clock]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=290710041 |title=Syracuse survives longest game in Big East history with epic win over UConn |accessdate=2009-03-13 |date=2009-03-12 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |work=[[ESPN]] |location=[[New York City]] }}</ref> Two other men's basketball games that involved teams now in NCAA Division I reached six overtime periods, both occurring in the era before the NCAA officially split into competitive divisions. [[Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball|Niagara]] defeated [[Siena Saints men's basketball|Siena]] 88\u201381 in 1953, and [[Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball|Minnesota]] defeated [[Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball|Purdue]] 59\u201356 in 1955. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UConn Huskies men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Syracuse Orange men's basketball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Big East Conference men's basketball season]]\n[[Category:College basketball games in the United States]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Orange men's basketball]]\n[[Category:UConn Huskies men's basketball]]\n[[Category:March 2009 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2009 in sports in New York City]]\n[[Category:Basketball in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college basketball game}}\n{{Infobox NCAABasketballSingleGame\n| Name               = 2009 Connecticut vs. Syracuse<br>\"6-overtime game\"\n| Type               = Big East Tournament Quarterfinals\n| Image              = \n| Date               = Thursday, March 12, 2009 to Friday, March 13, 2009\n| Year               = 2008-08\n| Visitor School     = Syracuse University\n| Visitor Name Short = Syracuse\n| Visitor Nickname   = Orange\n| Visitor Record     = 24\u20138\n| Visitor AP         = 18\n| Visitor Coaches    = 20\n| Visitor Coach      = [[Jim Boeheim]]\n| Visitor1           = 34\n| Visitor2           = 37\n| VisitorOT1         = 10\n| VisitorOT2         = 6\n| VisitorOT3         = 11\n| VisitorOT4         = 6\n| VisitorOT5         = 6\n| VisitorOT6         = 17\n| Home School        = University of Connecticut\n| Home Name Short    = Connecticut\n| Home Nickname      = Huskies\n| Home Record        = 27\u20133\n| Home AP            = 3\n| Home Coaches       = 4\n| Home Coach         = [[Jim Calhoun]]\n| Home1              = 37\n| Home2              = 34\n| HomeOT1            = 10\n| HomeOT2            = 6\n| HomeOT3            = 11\n| HomeOT4            = 6\n| HomeOT5            = 6\n| HomeOT6            = 7\n| Arena              = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n| City               = [[Manhattan|New York, New York]]\n| Attendance         = 19,375\n| US Network         = [[College Basketball on ESPN|ESPN]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Sean McDonough]], [[Bill Raftery]] and [[Jay Bilas]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2009 Connecticut vs. Syracuse men's basketball game''' was a quarterfinal game of the [[2009 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]] between the No. 18 [[2008\u201309 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse Orange]] (No. 6 seed in Big East Tournament) and No. 3 [[2008\u201309 Connecticut Huskies men's basketball team|Connecticut (UConn) Huskies]]. The 2009 UConn\u2013Syracuse basketball game took place on March 12, 2009 at [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City]], more specifically in [[Manhattan]].\n\nThis quarterfinal game of the 2009 Big East Tournament went to six overtimes, resulting in a 127\u2013117 Syracuse victory. The Orange won the game without leading at any time during the first five overtimes. The game began at 9:36{{nbsp}}p.m. and ended at 1:22{{nbsp}}a.m. on March 13, 2009, spanning 3 hours and 46 minutes. During the game, 244 total points were scored (102 scored during overtime), 211 field goals were attempted (103 attempted in overtime), 93 free throws were attempted, 66 fouls were committed, and eight total players fouled out (four from each team).\n\nThis game was the second-longest in college basketball history and the longest in Big East history. The longest game in college basketball history was the 1981 [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]] vs. [[Bradley Braves men's basketball|Bradley]] game in which [[1981 Bradley vs. Cincinnati men's basketball game|Cincinnati beat Bradley 75\u201373 on December 21, 1981]]. That game took place before the implementation of the [[shot clock]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=290710041 |title=Syracuse survives longest game in Big East history with epic win over UConn |accessdate=2009-03-13 |date=2009-03-12 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |work=[[ESPN]] |location=[[New York City]] }}</ref> Two other men's basketball games that involved teams now in NCAA Division I reached six overtime periods, both occurring in the era before the NCAA officially split into competitive divisions. [[Niagara Purple Eagles men's basketball|Niagara]] defeated [[Siena Saints men's basketball|Siena]] 88\u201381 in 1953, and [[Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball|Minnesota]] defeated [[Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball|Purdue]] 59\u201356 in 1955. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{UConn Huskies men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Syracuse Orange men's basketball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:College basketball games in the United States]]\n[[Category:Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Big East Conference men's basketball season]]\n[[Category:2009 in sports in New York City]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Orange men's basketball]]\n[[Category:UConn Huskies men's basketball]]\n[[Category:Basketball in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Connecticut_vs._Syracuse_men%27s_basketball_game"}
{"title_page": "Maximilian I of Mexico", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Maximilian I\n| image        = File:Maximilian of Mexico bw.jpg\n| caption      = circa 1864\n| reign        = 10 April 1864 \u2013 19 June 1867<ref>{{Britannica|id=370459}}</ref>\n| succession   = [[Emperor of Mexico]]\n|regent = {{List collapsed|title=List|[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lacunza|Jos\u00e9 Lacunza]]<br/>[[Teodosio Lares]]<br/>[[Santiago Vidaurri]]}}\n|reg-type = [[President of the Council of Ministers of the Mexican Empire|Prime Ministers]]\n| predecessor  = Monarchy re-established<br/><small>([[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], President of Mexico)</small><br/>[[Agustin I of Mexico]] <br/><small>(as Emperor)\n| successor    = Monarchy abolished<br/><small>([[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], President of Mexico)</small>\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Carlota of Mexico|Charlotte of Belgium]]|27 July 1857}}\n| full name    = {{lang-de|Ferdinand Maximilian Joseph Maria}}<br />{{lang-es|Fernando Maximiliano Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda}}<br />{{lang-en|Ferdinand Maximilian Joseph Maria}}\n| house        = [[Habsburg-Lorraine]]\n| father       = [[Archduke Franz Karl of Austria]]\n| mother       = [[Princess Sophie of Bavaria]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1832|7|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Sch\u00f6nbrunn Palace]], [[Vienna]], [[Austrian Empire]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1867|6|19|1832|7|6|df=y}}\n| death_place  = Cerro de las Campanas, [[Santiago de Quer\u00e9taro]], [[Second Mexican Empire|Mexican Empire]]\n| burial_place = [[Imperial Crypt]], [[Vienna]], Austria\n| signature    = Maximilian signature BW.png\n| signature_alt= Cursive signature in ink\n| religion     = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n'''Maximilian I''' ({{lang-es|Fernando Maximiliano Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda de Habsburgo-Lorena}}; 6 July 1832 \u2013 19 June 1867) was the only monarch of the [[Second Mexican Empire]]. He was a younger brother of the [[Austrian emperor]] [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph I]]. After a distinguished career in the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy|Austrian Navy]] as its commander, he accepted an offer by [[Napoleon III]] of France to rule Mexico, conditional on a national plebiscite in his favour. France, together with Spain and the United Kingdom, [[Second French intervention in Mexico|invaded the Mexican Republic]] in the winter of 1861, ostensibly to collect debts; the Spanish and British both withdrew the following year after negotiating agreements with Mexico's republican government, while France sought to conquer the country. Seeking to legitimize French rule, Napoleon III invited Maximilian to establish a new pro-[[Second French Empire|French]] Mexican monarchy. With the support of the French army and a group of [[Conservative Party (Mexico)|Conservative Party]] monarchists hostile to the [[Liberal Party (Mexico)|Liberal Party]] administration of the new Mexican president, [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], Maximilian was offered the position of [[Emperor of Mexico]], which he accepted on 10 April 1864.<ref name=\"RoyalArk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalark.net/Mexico/mexico4.htm|title=MEXICO4|website=www.royalark.net}}</ref>\n\nThe Empire managed to gain the recognition of several European powers, including Britain, Austria, and Prussia.{{sfn|Harding|1934|pp=175}} The United States however, continued to recognize Ju\u00e1rez as the legal president of Mexico. Maximilian never completely defeated the Mexican Republic; Republican forces led by Ju\u00e1rez continued to be active during Maximilian's rule. With the end of the [[American Civil War]] in 1865, the United States (which had been too distracted by its own conflict to respond to the Europeans' 1861 invasion in what it considered to be its [[sphere of influence]]) began providing more explicit aid to Ju\u00e1rez's forces. Matters worsened for Maximilian after French armies withdrew from Mexico in 1866. The Empire collapsed, and he was captured and executed by the Mexican government, which then restored the Mexican Republic.\n\nHis wife, [[Carlota of Mexico|Charlotte of Belgium]], who had left for Europe earlier to try to build support for her husband's regime, suffered an emotional collapse after his death and apparently became insane.<ref>{{cite news\n|newspaper=[[New York Times]]\n|date=March 6, 1885\n|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1885/03/06/102957723.pdf\n|title=Charlotte of Mexico's Misfortune}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Birth===\n[[File:Emperor Maximilian of Mexico as a boy.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Maximilian as a boy, 1838]]\nMaximilian was born on 6 July 1832 in the [[Sch\u00f6nbrunn Palace]] in [[Vienna]], capital of the [[Austrian Empire]].{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=6}}{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=4}}{{sfn|Corti|1929|p=41}} He was baptized the following day as ''Ferdinand Maximilian Joseph''. The first name honored his godfather and paternal uncle, [[Ferdinand I of Austria|Ferdinand I]], King of Hungary, and the second honored his maternal grandfather, [[Maximilian I Joseph of Bavaria|Maximilian I Joseph]], King of Bavaria.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|pp=6\u20137}}{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=5}}\n\nHis father was [[Archduke Franz Karl of Austria|Archduke Franz Karl]], the second surviving son of [[Francis II, Holy Roman Emperor]], during whose reign he was born. Maximilian was thus a member of the [[House of Lorraine|House of Habsburg-Lorraine]], a female-line cadet branch of the [[House of Habsburg]].{{sfn|Palmer|1994|pp=3, 5}} His mother was [[Princess Sophie of Bavaria]], a member of the [[House of Wittelsbach]].{{sfn|Palmer|1994|p=3}} Intelligent, ambitious and strong-willed, Sophie had little in common with her husband, whom historian Richard O'Conner characterized as \"an amiably dim fellow whose main interest in life was consuming bowls of dumplings drenched in gravy\".{{sfn|O'Connor|1971|p=29}} Despite their different personalities, the marriage was fruitful, and after four miscarriages, four sons\u2014including Maximilian\u2014would reach adulthood.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=7}}\n\nRumors at the court stated that Maximilian was, in fact, the product of an extramarital affair between his mother and his first cousin [[Napoleon II of France|Napoleon II, Duke of Reichstadt]], the only legitimate son of [[Napoleon]]; the duke's mother was [[Marie Louise, Duchess of Parma]], former Empress of the French, Maximilian's aunt.{{sfn|Ridley|2001|p=44}} The existence of an illicit affair between Sophie and the duke, and any possibility that Maximilian was conceived from such a union, are dubious.{{ref label|specialnotes1|A|none}}\n\n===Education===\n[[File:Ferdinand_Maximilian_of_Austria_Litho.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Archduke Ferdinand Maximilian of Austria, later Maximilian I Emperor of Mexico. Lithography.]]\n\nAdhering to traditions inherited from the Spanish court during Habsburg rule, Maximilian's upbringing was closely supervised. Until his sixth birthday, he was cared for by Baroness [[Louise von Sturmfeder]], who was his ''aja'' (then rendered \"nurse\", now [[nanny]]). Afterward, his education was entrusted to a tutor.{{sfn|Hyde|1946|pp=6\u20137}} Most of Maximilian's day was spent in study. The hours per week of classes steadily increased from 32 at age seven to 55 by the time he was 17.{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=7}} The disciplines were diverse, ranging from history, geography, law and technology, to languages, military studies, fencing and diplomacy.{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=7}} In addition to his native [[German language|German]], he eventually learned to speak [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]].{{sfn|Hall|1868|p=17}} From an early age, Maximilian tried to surpass his older brother Franz Joseph in everything, attempting to prove to all that he was the better qualified of the two and thus deserving of more than second-place status.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=17}}\n\n[[File:Maximiliaan_van_Oostenrijk.png|thumb|right|250px|Maximilian painting.]]\n\nThe highly restrictive environment of the Austrian court was not enough to repress Maximilian's natural openness. He was joyful, highly charismatic and able to captivate those around him with ease. Although he was a charming boy, he was also undisciplined.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=11}} He mocked his teachers and was often the instigator of pranks\u2014even including his uncle, the emperor, among his victims.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|pp=14\u201315}} Nonetheless, Maximilian was very popular. His attempts to outshine his older brother and ability to charm opened a rift with the aloof and self-contained Franz Joseph that would widen as years passed, and their close friendship in childhood would be all but forgotten.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=17}}\n\nIn 1848, [[Revolutions of 1848|revolutions erupted across Europe]]. In the face of protests and riots, Emperor Ferdinand&nbsp;I abdicated in favor of Maximilian's brother, who became Francis&nbsp;Joseph&nbsp;I.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=29}}{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=13}} Maximilian accompanied him on campaigns to put down rebellions throughout the empire.{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=31}}{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=13}} Only in 1849 would the revolution be stamped out in Austria, with hundreds of rebels executed and thousands imprisoned. Maximilian was horrified at what he regarded as senseless brutality and openly complained about it. He would later remark, \"We call our age the Age of Enlightenment, but there are cities in Europe where, in the future, men will look back in horror and amazement at the injustice of tribunals, which in a spirit of vengeance condemned to death those whose only crime lay in wanting something different to the arbitrary rule of governments which placed themselves above the law\".{{sfn|Haslip|1972|p=34}}{{sfn|Hyde|1946|p=14}}\n\n===Marriage and life in Mexico===\n[[File:Retrato de Emperador Fernando Maximiliano I de M\u00e9xico (c. 1864).tif|thumb|250px|Emperor Fernando Maximiliano I of M\u00e9xico portrait (c. 1864).]]\n[[File:Maximilian_I_of_Mexico_portrait_standing.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico, circa 1857-1867.]]\n\nFerdinand Maximilian Joseph married Princess [[Carlota of Mexico|Charlotte of Belgium]], daughter of King [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]], on 27 July 1857. The couple lived in Milan until 1859, and then they moved to [[Trieste]]. In 1859, they sailed to [[Madeira]], where Maria Amelia de Orleans y Braganza, daughter of Emperor [[Pedro I of Brazil]] was buried. He and Maria Amelia had once been engaged, and it is said she was the love of his life. Shortly afterward, Maximilian went to Brazil, leaving Charlotte in Madeira.<ref>{{cite book|title=99 Pasiones en la Historia de Mexico|author=Alejandro Rosas|language=Spanish|trans-title=99 Passions in Mexican History|publisher=Editorial Planta Mexican|location=Mexico City |edition=1st|date=2012|isbn=9786070712067|pages=42\u201345}}</ref>\n\nOnce offered the crown of Mexico, Maximilian and Charlotte sailed from Trieste on 10 April 1864, and arrived in [[Veracruz]] on 28 May [[1864 in Mexico|1864]]. Maximilian had demanded a [[Referendum|plebiscite]] on his rule, but it turned out to be a farce, and when the couple arrived in Veracruz there was little support from the people.<ref>{{cite web|title=La Corona Envenenada de Maximiliano de Habsburgo |url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/historiayvida/maximiliano-emperador-de-mexico_11491_102.html |website=Historia y Vida|language=Spanish |trans-title=The Poisoned Crown of Maximilian of Hasburg|accessdate=June 7, 2019|first=Isabel|last=Margarit|date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Nonetheless, when they celebrated Charlotte's birthday in [[Puebla]] in June of that year, the people donated 1,604 pesos as a birthday present.<ref>{{cite web|title=1864: Maximiliano y Carlota llegan al puerto de Veracruz|url=https://www.poblanerias.com/2016/05/1864-maximiliano-y-carlota-llegan-al-puerto-de-veracruz/|website=Poblarnarias.com|language=Spanish |trans-title=1864: Maximilian and Charlotte arrive at the port of Veracruz|accessdate=June 7, 2019|date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom Puebla they went to Mexico City, where they established the royal residence in [[Chapultepec Castle]], which had previously been a military academy. The castle was remodeled and richly furnished. He built wide boulevards such as [[Paseo de la Reforma|Paseo de la Emperatriz (\"Promenade of the Empress\")]] in Mexico City, and instituted liberal social reforms (much to the chagrin of his conservative base). The couple adopted both grandsons of Emperor [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide]]. The couple bought the [[Borda Garden]] in Cuernavaca, and he bought a country estate for his mistress, [[Concepcion Sedano]], in suburban [[Acapantzingo, Cuernavaca|Acapantzingo]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Acapantzingo, Tierra Florida de History y Tradiciones|author=Ma. Cristina Toledano Vergara|date=1999|publisher=CONACULTA|location=Cuernavaca|pages=47\u201351 |language=Spanish|trans-title=Acapantzingo, Flowery land of history and traditions}}</ref>\n\nFrance withdrew the troops who had propped up Maximilian in 1867; Mexico City soon fell to the liberal forces of [[Benito Juarez]], the emperor was arrested, and on 19 June 1867 he was executed. His last words were, \"I forgive everyone, and I ask everyone to forgive me. May my blood which is about to be shed, be for the good of the country. Viva Mexico, viva la independencia!\" Some say he then mumbled, \"Poor Carlota!\"<ref name=\"star crossed\">{{cite web|title=Maximilian; Star Crossed Emperor of Mexico |url=http://www.revisionist.net/hysteria/maximilian.html|website=Revisionist.net|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career in the Austrian Navy==\n===Commander-in-Chief===\n[[File:Maximilian around 1850.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Portrait of Archduke Maximilian in uniform of naval officer, c. 1850]] Maximilian was a particularly clever boy who displayed considerable culture in his taste for the arts, and he demonstrated an early interest in [[science]], especially [[botany]]. When he entered military service, he was trained in the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy|Austrian Navy]]. He threw himself into this career with so much zeal that he quickly rose to high command.<ref>Antonio Schmidt-Brentano'' The Austrian admirals'' Volume I, 1808\u20131895, Library Verlag, Osnabr\u00fcck 1997, pp. 93\u2013104.</ref>\n\n[[File:Maximiliano_1852.png|thumb|250px|Maximiliano with no beard at 20 years, 1852.]]\n\nHe was made a lieutenant in the navy at the age of eighteen. In 1854, he sailed as commander in the [[corvette]] ''Minerva'', on an exploring expedition along the coast of Albania and Dalmatia. Maximilian was especially interested in maritime matters and undertook many long-distance journeys (for [[Brazil]]) on the [[frigate]] ''Elisabeth''.<ref>Ferdinand Maximilian of Austria Maximilian, Archduke of Austria:''From My Life Reiseskizzen, aphorisms, poems,'' Volume 6:.''Reiseskizzen'' Part 11 2 Edition. Duncker and Humblot, Leipzig, 1867</ref> In 1854, he was only 22 years\u2014as a younger brother of the emperor, and thus a member of the ruling family\u2014he was appointed as commander-in-chief of the Austrian Navy (1854\u20131861),<ref>Antonio Schmidt-Brentano: [http://www.oesta.gv.at/DocView.axd?CobId=23130 ''Die K.K bzw. K.u.K Generalit\u00e4t 1816\u20131918''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215757/http://www.oesta.gv.at/DocView.axd?CobId=23130 |date=2013-10-04 }}. \u00d6sterreichisches Staatsarchiv, Wien 2007, S. 130 (PDF).</ref> which he reorganized in the following years. Like [[Friedrich Ferdinand Leopold of Austria|Archduke Friedrich]] (1821\u20131847) before him, Maximilian had a keen personal interest in the fleet, and with him the Austrian naval force gained an influential supporter from the ranks of the [[House of Habsburg|imperial family]]. This was crucial, as sea power had never been a priority of Austrian foreign policy, and the navy itself was relatively little known or supported by the public. It was only able to draw significant public attention and funds when it was actively supported by an imperial prince. As commander-in-chief, Maximilian carried out many reforms to modernise the naval forces, and was instrumental in creating the naval port at [[Trieste]] and Pola (now [[Pula]]), as well as the battle fleet with which Admiral [[Wilhelm von Tegetthoff]] would later secure his victories. He also initiated a large-scale [[SMS Novara (1850)#Novara Expedition|scientific expedition (1857\u20131859)]] during which the frigate [[SMS Novara (1850)|SMS ''Novara'']] became the first Austrian warship to [[circumnavigation|circumnavigate]] the globe.\n\n===Viceroy of Lombardy-Venetia===\n[[File:Schloss_miramare.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[Miramare Castle]] at the beginning of the twenty-first century.]]\n\nIn his political views, Archduke Maximilian was very much influenced by the progressive ideas in vogue at the time. He had a reputation as a [[Liberalism|liberal]], and this was one of several considerations leading to his appointment as Viceroy of the [[Kingdom of Lombardy\u2013Venetia]] in February 1857. Emperor Franz Joseph had decided on the need to replace the elderly soldier [[Joseph Radetzky von Radetz]], to divert growing discontent amongst the Italian population through token liberalization, and to encourage a degree of personal loyalty to the Habsburg dynasty.<ref>{{cite book|first=Victoria|last=Highes|pages=38\u201339|title=A Lurid Grandeur. Maximillian and Carlota of Mexico|isbn=9-780692-723043|date=2016-06-09}}</ref>\n  \nOn 27 July 1857, in [[Brussels]], Archduke Maximilian married his second cousin Princess Charlotte of Belgium, the daughter of [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]], [[King of the Belgians]], and [[Louise of Orl\u00e9ans]]. She was first cousin to both [[Queen Victoria]] and [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]]. Maximilian and Charlotte had no children.\n\nThey lived as the Austrian regents in [[Milan]] or [[viceroy]]s of [[Kingdom of Lombardy\u2013Venetia|Lombardy-Venetia]] from 1857 until 1859, when Emperor Franz Joseph, angered by his brother's liberal policies, dismissed him. Shortly after, Austria lost control of most of its Italian possessions. Maximilian then retired to Trieste, near which he built [[Miramare Castle]]. At the same time, the couple acquired a converted monastery on the island of [[Lokrum]] as a holiday residence. Both estates had extensive gardens, reflecting Maximilian's horticultural interests.<ref>{{cite book|first=Gene|last=Smith|pages=[https://archive.org/details/maximiliancarlot00smit/page/81 81\u201383]|title=Maximillian and Carlotta|isbn=0-688-00173-4|year=1973|url=https://archive.org/details/maximiliancarlot00smit/page/81}}</ref>\n\n==Emperor of Mexico ==\n===Offer of the Mexican crown===\n{{See also|Imperial Crown of Mexico}}\n[[File:Dell'Acqua Ernennung Maximilians zum Kaiser Mexikos.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Maximilian receiving a Mexican delegation at [[Miramare Castle]] in [[Trieste]]. Painting by Cesare dell'Acqua (1821-1905).]]\nIn 1859, Ferdinand Maximilian was first approached by Mexican monarchists\u2014members of the [[Mexican Nobility|Mexican aristocracy]], led by local nobleman Jos\u00e9 Pablo [[Mart\u00ednez del R\u00edo]]\u2014with a proposal to become the Emperor of Mexico. The Habsburg family had ruled the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain]] from its establishment until [[War of Spanish Succession|the Spanish throne was inherited by the Bourbons]]. Maximilian was considered to have more potential legitimacy than other royal figures, but was unlikely to ever rule in Europe due to his elder brother.<ref name=\"maxinmexico\">{{Cite web|url=https://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/10/04/maximilian-in-mexico/|title=Maximilian in Mexico|first=Phil|last=Leigh|date=October 4, 2013}}</ref> On 20 October 1861 in Paris, Maximilian received a letter from [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez de Estrada|Gutierrez de Estrada]] asking him to take the Mexican throne. He did not accept at first, but sought to satisfy his restless desire for adventure with a botanical expedition to the [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|tropical forests]] of Brazil. However, Maximilian changed his mind after the [[Second French intervention in Mexico|French intervention in Mexico]]. At the invitation of [[Napoleon III]], after General [[\u00c9lie-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Forey]]'s capture of [[Mexico City]] and a French-staged [[plebiscite]] that confirmed the proclamation of the empire, Maximilian consented to accept the crown in October 1863.<ref name=\"maxinmexico\" /> His decision involved the loss of all his rights of nobility in Austria, though he was not informed of this until just before he left. Archduchess Charlotte was thereafter known as \"Her Imperial Majesty Empress Carlota\".\n\n===Reign in Mexico===\n{{See also|Second Mexican Empire}}\n\nIn April 1864, Archduke Ferdinand Maximilian stepped down from his duties as Chief of Naval Section of the Austrian Navy. He traveled from [[Trieste]] aboard [[SMS Novara (1850)|SMS ''Novara'']], escorted by the frigates {{SMS|Bellona}} (Austrian) and [[French frigate Th\u00e9mis (1862)|''Th\u00e9mis'']] (French), and the Imperial yacht ''Phantasie'' led the warship procession from his palace at [[Miramare]] out to sea.<ref>Haslip, Joan, ''Imperial Adventurer \u2013 Emperor Maximilian of Mexico'', London, 1971, {{ISBN|0-297-00363-1}}</ref> They received a blessing from [[Pope Pius IX]], and [[Queen Victoria]] ordered the Gibraltar garrison to fire a salute for Maximilian's passing ship.\n\n[[File:Maximilian_of_Mexico_by_Franz_Xaver_Winterhalter_(Hearst_Castle).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Maximilian of Mexico by [[Franz Xaver Winterhalter]] ([[Hearst Castle]])]]\n\nThe new emperor of Mexico landed at [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]] on 29 May 1864,<ref>{{cite book|first=Gene|last=Smith|page=[https://archive.org/details/maximiliancarlot00smit/page/159 159]|title=Maximillian and Carlotta|isbn=0-688-00173-4|year=1973|url=https://archive.org/details/maximiliancarlot00smit/page/159}}</ref> and received a cold reception from the townspeople. Veracruz was a liberal town, and the liberal voters were opposed to having Maximilian on the throne.{{sfn|Parkes|1960|p=261}} He had the backing of Mexican conservatives and [[Napoleon III]], but from the very outset he found himself involved in serious difficulties, since the Liberal forces led by President [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]] refused to recognize his rule. There was continuous fighting between the French expeditionary forces (who were supplemented by Maximilian's locally recruited imperial troops) on one side and the Mexican Republicans on the other.<ref>{{cite book|first=Rene|last=Chartrand|pages=18\u201323|title=The Mexican Adventure 1861-67|isbn=1-85532-430-X|date=1994-07-28}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Charlotte of Belgium.jpg|left|thumb|200px|[[Carlota of Mexico|Empress Charlotte]]]]\n\nThe Imperial couple chose as their seat [[Mexico City]]. The emperor and empress set up their residence at [[Chapultepec Castle]], located on the top of a hill formerly on the outskirts of Mexico City that had been a retreat of [[Aztec]] emperors. Maximilian ordered a wide avenue cut through the city from [[Chapultepec]] to the city center named Paseo de Chapultepec or Paseo de la Emperatriz.<ref>{{cite book|first=M. M.|last=McAllen|page=165|title=Maximilian and Carlota. Europe's Last Empire in Mexico|isbn=978-1-59534-263-8|date=April 2015}}</ref> He also acquired a country retreat at [[Cuernavaca]]. The royal couple made plans to be crowned at the [[Mexico City Metropolitan Cathedral|Catedral Metropolitana]], but due to the constant instability of the regime, the coronation was never carried out.<ref>{{cite book|first=Victoria|last=Hughes|page=133|title=A Lurid Grandeur. Maximilian & Carlota of Mexico.|isbn=9780692723043|date=2016-06-09}}</ref> Maximilian was shocked by the living conditions of the poor in contrast to the magnificent haciendas of the upper class. Empress Carlota began holding parties for wealthy Mexicans in order to raise money for poor houses.{{clarify|date=June 2019|reason=Poorhouses?}} One of Maximilian's first acts as emperor was to restrict working hours and abolish child labour. He cancelled all debts for peasants over 10 pesos, restored communal property, and forbade all forms of corporal punishment. He also broke the monopoly of the hacienda stores{{clarify|date=June 2019}}, and decreed that henceforth peons could no longer be bought and sold for the price of their debt.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nAs Maximilian and Carlota had no children, they adopted [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide y Green]] and his cousin [[Salvador de Iturbide y Marz\u00e1n|Salvador de Iturbide y de Marz\u00e1n]], both grandsons of [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide]], who had briefly reigned as Emperor of Mexico in the 1820s. Iturbide and his cousin were granted the title Prince de Iturbide and the style of Highness by an imperial decree of 16 September 1865, and were ranked next in line after the reigning family.<ref>{{cite wikisource |title=Decreto Imperial del 16 de Septiembre de 1865 |wslanguage=es}}</ref> Apparently, the royal couple intended to groom Agust\u00edn as heir to the throne. \n\n[[File:Francis_joseph_with_brothers_1859.png|thumb|right|200px|[[Emperor]] [[Francis Joseph I.]] of Austria-Hungary beside his brothers. From left to right: [[Archduke Ludwig Viktor of Austria]], [[Kaiser]] [[Franz Josef]], [[Archduke Karl Ludwig of Austria]], [[Archduke]] Ferdinand Maximilian of Austria, Emperor of Mexico.]]\n\nHowever, in reality Maximilian never intended to give the crown to the Iturbides because he believed that they were not of royal blood.<ref name=rosas /> It was all a charade directed at his brother [[Archduke Karl Ludwig of Austria]], as Maximilian explained himself: either Karl would give him one of his sons as an heir, or else he would bequeath everything to the Iturbide children.<ref name=rosas>{{citation |title= Presidentes de M\u00e9xico |author= Jos\u00e9 Manuel Villalpando, Alejandro Rosas |publisher= Grupo Planeta Spain |year= 2011 |isbn= 9786070707582 |pages=are not numbered |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=H2TbqVzLhOYC&pg=PT326 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maximilian_of_Mexico_Winterhalter.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Maximilian of Mexico by Franz Xaver Winterhalter.]]\n\nTo the dismay of his conservative allies, Maximilian upheld several liberal policies proposed by the Ju\u00e1rez administration, such as land reforms, religious freedom, and extending the right to vote beyond the landholding classes. At first, Maximilian offered Ju\u00e1rez an amnesty if he would swear allegiance to the crown, even offering him the post of prime minister, which Ju\u00e1rez refused.<ref>{{cite book|first=M. M.|last=McAllen|page=116|title=Maximilian and Carlota. Europe's Last Empire in Mexico|isbn=978-1-59534-263-8|date=April 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Css Image Crop|Image = Mexico 1866 20 Pesos.jpg |bSize = 445|cWidth = 220|cHeight = 220|oTop = 3|oLeft = 2|Location = right|Description=Maximilian I of Mexico depicted on a 20-[[Mexican peso|peso]] gold coin (1866)}}\n\nAfter the end of the [[American Civil War]], President [[Andrew Johnson]] invoked the [[Monroe Doctrine]] and recognized the Juarez government as the legitimate government of Mexico. The United States applied increasing diplomatic pressure to persuade Napoleon III to end French support of Maximilian and to withdraw French troops from Mexico. Washington began supplying partisans of Ju\u00e1rez and his ally [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]] by \"losing\" arms depots to them at [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez|El Paso del Norte]] at the Mexican border.<ref name=\"star crossed\" /> The prospect of an American invasion to reinstate Ju\u00e1rez caused a large number of Maximilian's loyal adherents to abandon his cause and leave the capital.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Paul H. |last=Reuter |title=United States-French Relations Regarding French Intervention in Mexico: From the Tripartite Treaty to Quer\u00e9taro |journal=Southern Quarterly |year=1965 |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=469\u2013489 }}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Maximilian invited ex-Confederates to move to Mexico in a series of settlements called the \"Carlota Colony\" and the [[New Virginia Colony]], with a dozen others being considered, a plan conceived by the internationally renowned U.S. Navy oceanographer and inventor [[Matthew Fontaine Maury]]. Maximilian also invited settlers from \"any country\", including Austria and the other German states.<ref>{{cite book |last=Rolle |first=Andrew F. |title=The Lost Cause: The Confederate Exodus to Mexico |location= |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |year=1992 |isbn=0-8061-1961-6 }}</ref>\n\nMaximilian issued his \"Black Decree\"' on 3 October 1865. Its first article stated that: \"All individuals forming a part of armed bands or bodies existing without legal authority, whether or not proclaiming a political pretext, whatever the number of those forming such band, or its organization, character, and denomination, shall be judged militarily by the courts martial. If found guilty, even though only of the fact of belonging to an armed band, they shall be condemned to capital punishment, and the sentence shall be executed within twenty-four hours\". It is calculated that more than eleven thousand of Juarez's supporters were executed as a result of the decree, but in the end it only inflamed the Mexican resistance.<ref name=Milles>{{citation |title= Cinco de Mayo: What is Everybody Celebrating? : the Story Behind Mexico's Battle of Puebla |author= Donald W. Miles |publisher= iUniverse |year= 2006 |isbn= 9780595392414 |page=196 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ek-vNWcSt44C&q=black+decree#v=snippet&q=black%20decree&f=false }}</ref><ref name=Ridley>{{citation |title= Maximilian and Ju\u00e1rez |author= Jasper Ridley |publisher= Constable |year= 1993 |isbn= 9780094720701 |page=229 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=59V6AAAAMAAJ&q=%2211%2C000+victims%22 }}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, by 1866, the imminence of Maximilian's [[abdication]] seemed apparent to almost everyone outside Mexico. That year, Napoleon III withdrew his troops in the face of Mexican resistance and U.S. opposition under the Monroe Doctrine, as well as to strengthen his forces at home to face the ever-growing [[Prussia]]n military and [[Otto von Bismarck|Bismarck]]. Carlota travelled to Europe, seeking assistance for her husband's regime in Paris and Vienna and, finally, in Rome from [[Pope Pius IX]]. Her efforts failed, and she suffered a deep emotional collapse and never went back to Mexico. After her husband was executed by Republicans the following year, she spent the rest of her life in seclusion, never admitting her husband's death, first at Miramare Castle in Trieste, Austria-Hungary, then Italy, and then at [[Bouchout Castle]] in [[Meise]], Belgium,<ref name=\"NYTimes-6-mar-1885\">\"[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1885/03/06/102957723.pdf Charlotte of Mexico's Misfortune]\", ''New York Times'', March 6, 1885.</ref> where she died on 19 January 1927.<ref name=\"NYTimes-19-jan-1927\">\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1927/01/20/archives/belgium-mourns-for-dead-empress-tragedy-of-life-of-charlotte-wife.html?sq=Charlotte%2520of%2520Mexico&scp=10&st=cse Belgium Mourns for Dead Empress; Tragedy of Life of Charlotte, Wife of Maximilian, Is Recalled]\", ''New York Times'', 19 January 1927.</ref>\n\n===Downfall===\n[[File:The Last moments of Maximilian.jpg|thumb|Last moments of Emperor Maximilian I of M\u00e9xico. by [[Jean-Paul Laurens]]]]\n[[File:Edouard Manet 022.jpg|thumb|[[\u00c9douard Manet]]'s ''[[Execution of Emperor Maximilian]]'' (1868\u20131869), is one of five versions of his representation of the execution of the Austrian-born Emperor of Mexico, which took place on June 19, 1867. Manet borrowed heavily, thematically and technically, from Goya's ''[[The Third of May 1808]]''.]]\n\nThough urged to abandon Mexico by Napoleon III himself, whose troop withdrawal from Mexico was a great blow to the Mexican Imperial cause, Maximilian refused to desert his followers. Maximilian allowed his followers to determine whether or not he abdicated.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Faithful generals such as [[Miguel Miram\u00f3n]], [[Leonardo M\u00e1rquez]], and [[Tom\u00e1s Mej\u00eda]] vowed to raise an army that would challenge the invading Republicans. Maximilian fought on with his army of 8,000 Mexican loyalists. Withdrawing, in February 1867, to [[Santiago de Quer\u00e9taro]], he sustained [[Siege of Quer\u00e9taro|a siege]] for several weeks, but on May 11 resolved to attempt an escape through the enemy lines. This plan was sabotaged by Colonel Miguel L\u00f3pez who was bribed by the Republicans to open a gate and lead a raiding party, though with the agreement that Maximilian would be allowed to escape.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n[[File:Photography of Execution of Maximilian I of Mexico, Miram\u00f3n and Mej\u00eda \u2014 1867.jpg|thumb|left|Execution of Mej\u00eda, Miram\u00f3n and Maximilian (at right). While no photograph was taken of the actual execution, an on-the-spot sketch made by eyewitness Fran\u00e7ois Aubert indicates that this is an accurate reconstruction<ref>{{cite book|first=M. M.|last=McAllen|page=386|title=Maximilian and Carlota. Europe's Last Empire in Mexico|isbn=978-1-59534-263-8|date=April 2015}}</ref>]]\n\nThe city fell on 15 May 1867 and Maximilian was captured the next morning after the failure of an attempt to escape through Republican lines by a loyal [[hussar]] cavalry brigade led by [[Felix Salm-Salm]]. Following a [[court-martial]], he was sentenced to death. Many of the crowned heads of Europe and other prominent figures (including the eminent liberals [[Victor Hugo]] and [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]]) sent telegrams and letters to Mexico pleading desperately for the Emperor's life to be spared. Although he liked Maximilian on a personal level,<ref name=\"Maximilian_and_Carlota\">''Maximilian and Carlota'' by Gene Smith, {{ISBN|0-245-52418-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-245-52418-9}}</ref> Ju\u00e1rez refused to commute the sentence in view of the Mexicans who had been killed fighting against Maximilian's forces, and because he believed it was necessary to send a message that Mexico would not tolerate any government imposed by foreign powers. [[Felix Salm-Salm]] and his wife masterminded a plan and bribed the jailors to allow Maximilian to escape execution. However, Maximilian would not go through with the plan because he felt that shaving his beard to avoid recognition would ruin his dignity if he were to be recaptured.{{sfn|Parkes|1960|p=273}} The sentence was carried out in the ''[[Cerro de las Campanas]]'' at 6:40&nbsp;a.m. on the morning of 19 June 1867, when Maximilian, along with Generals Miram\u00f3n and Mej\u00eda, was executed by a firing squad. He spoke only in Spanish and gave each of his executioners a gold coin not to shoot him in the head so that his mother could see his face. His last words were, \"I forgive everyone, and I ask everyone to forgive me. May my blood, which is about to be shed, be for the good of the country. Viva Mexico, viva la independencia!\"<ref>Giving executer(s) a portion of gold/silver is well-established among European aristocracy since medieval time and not an act of desperation. In other accounts, Maximilian calmly said, \"aim well\", to the firing squad and met his death with dignity.</ref> Generals Miram\u00f3n and Mej\u00eda standing to Maximilian's right, were killed by the same volley as the emperor, fired by the fifteen-man (twenty-one in other accounts) execution party. Maximilian and Miram\u00f3n died almost immediately, the emperor calling out the single word ''hombre'', but Mej\u00eda's death was a more extended one.<ref>{{cite book|first=M. M.|last=McAllen|page=387|title=Maximilian and Carlota. Europe's Last Empire in Mexico|isbn=978-1-59534-263-8|date=April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Burial==\n[[File:Francois Aubert 2.jpg|thumb|right|Maximilian's embalmed body]]\nAfter his execution, Maximilian's body was embalmed and displayed in Mexico. Early the following year, the Austrian admiral [[Wilhelm von Tegetthoff]] was sent to Mexico aboard [[SMS Novara (1850)|SMS ''Novara'']] to take the former emperor's body back to Austria. After arriving in Trieste, the coffin was taken to [[Vienna, Austria|Vienna]] and placed within the [[Imperial Crypt]], on 18 January 1868, where it can be viewed today.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nThe [[Emperor Maximilian Memorial Chapel]] was constructed on the hill where his execution took place.<ref>{{cite book|author=Benito Ju\u00e1rez|url=http://www.diputados.gob.mx/sedia/biblio/virtual/bicentena/fusil_max/03_fusil_maxi1.pdf|title=Manifiesto justificativo de los castigos nacionales en Quer\u00e9taro|date=2010|publisher=Chamber of Deputies, [[LXI Legislature of the Mexican Congress|LXI Legislature]]|contribution=Preface: \"El fusilamiento de Maximiliano de Habsburgo\"|contributor1=Isa\u00ed Hidekel Tejada Vallejo}}<!--for publishing info - http://www.diputados.gob.mx/sedia/biblio/virtual/bicentena/fusil_max/02_present.pdf --></ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Paseo Ju\u00e1rez \"El Llano\" 05.JPG|thumbnail|left|Sculpture of [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]] made in 1894 at Paseo Ju\u00e1rez \"El Llano\" in the Historic Centre of [[Oaxaca, Oaxaca|Oaxaca]]. Ju\u00e1rez holds a [[Mexican flag]] with one hand and with the other is pointing to Maximilian's [[Imperial Crown of Mexico]] which remains in the soil, representing the defeat of the [[Second Mexican Empire]].]]\nMaximilian has been praised by some historians for his liberal reforms, genuine desire to help the people of Mexico, refusal to desert his loyal followers, and personal bravery during the siege of Quer\u00e9taro. Other researchers consider him short-sighted in political and military affairs, and unwilling to restore democracy in Mexico even during the imminent collapse of the [[Second Mexican Empire]]. Today, anti-republican and anti-liberal political groups who advocate the Second Mexican Empire, such as the [[Nationalist Front of Mexico]], are reported to gather every year in Quer\u00e9taro to commemorate the execution of Maximilian and his followers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacionalistas.org/2012/06/homenaje-los-martires-del-segundo.html |title=Homage to the Martyrs of the Second Mexican Empire |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503115911/http://www.nacionalistas.org/2012/06/homenaje-los-martires-del-segundo.html |archivedate=2014-05-03 }}</ref> Maximilian is portrayed in the 1934 Mexican film ''[[Ju\u00e1rez y Maximiliano]]'' by [[Enrique Herrera (actor)|Enrique Herrera]] and the 1939 American film ''[[Juarez (film)|Juarez]]'' by [[Brian Aherne]]. He also appeared in one scene in the 1954 American film ''[[Vera Cruz (film)|Vera Cruz]]'', played by [[George Macready]]. In the Mexican [[telenovela]] [[:es:El vuelo del \u00e1guila|''El Vuelo del \u00c1guila'']], Maximilian was portrayed by Mexican actor [[Mario Iv\u00e1n Mart\u00ednez]].\n\nIn the wake of his death, [[carte-de-visite]] cards with photographs commemorating his execution circulated both among his followers and among those who wished to celebrate his death. One such card featured a photograph of the shirt he wore to his execution, riddled with bullet holes.<ref>Laughlin, Eleanor A. \"Carte-de-visite Photograph of Maximilian von Habsburg's Execution Shirt\". Object Narrative. In Conversations: An Online Journal of the Center for the Study of Material and Visual Cultures of Religion (2016). doi:10.22332/con.obj.2016.1 http://mavcor.yale.edu/conversations/object-narratives/carte-de-visite-photograph-maximilian-von-habsburg-s-execution-shirt</ref>\n\nThe composer [[Franz Liszt]] included a \"Marche fun\u00e8bre, en m\u00e9moire de Maximilian I, empereur de Mexique\" (a funeral march, in memory of Maximilian I, Emperor of Mexico) among the pieces in his famous collection of piano pieces entitled ''[[Ann\u00e9es de p\u00e8lerinage]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/dw.asp?dc=W7877_GBAJY9941410|title=En m\u00e9moire de Maximilien I \u2013 Marche fun\u00e8bre, S162d (Liszt) - from CDA67414/7 - Hyperion Records - MP3 and Lossless downloads|website=www.hyperion-records.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe crown jewels of the Second Mexican Empire are on display at the [[Imperial_Treasury,_Vienna|Schatzkammer Museum]] in the [[Hofburg Palace]] in Vienna.\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n[[File:Imperial Monogram of Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico.svg|thumb|right|140px|Imperial Monogram]]\n\n===Titles and styles===\n* '''6 July 1832 - 10 April 1864''': ''His Imperial and Royal Highness'' Archduke and Prince Ferdinand Maximilian of Austria, Prince of Hungary, Bohemia and Croatia<ref name=\"harmonische Wahlkapitulation\">{{cite book|title=Kaiser Joseph II. harmonische Wahlkapitulation mit allen den vorhergehenden Wahlkapitulationen der vorigen Kaiser und K\u00f6nige}} Since 1780 official title used for princes (\"''zu Ungarn, B\u00f6hmen, Dalmatien, Kroatien, Slawonien, K\u00f6niglicher Erbprinz''\")</ref>\n* '''10 April 1864 - 19 June 1867''': ''His Imperial Majesty'' The Emperor of Mexico\n\n===Honours===\n[[File:Maxmexhietzing.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Maximilian I monument with the number 75741 in Austria.]]\n[[File:Busto en yeso de Maximiliano y Carlota de Habsburgo.JPG|thumb|right|Bust of Maximiliano and Carlota at the [[Museo Soumaya]] in Mexico City.]]\n[[File:Kaiser Maximilian I of Mexico.jpg|thumb|Bust by an anonymous sculptor on display at the [[Heeresgeschichtliches Museum]] - Vienna, Austria, 2013.]]\n;Domestic<ref name=\"RoyalArk\"/>\n* Grand Master of the [[Mexican Imperial Orders#Order of the Order of Guadalupe|Order of Guadalupe]]\n* Founder and Grand Master of the [[Mexican Imperial Orders#Order of the Mexican Eagle|Order of the Mexican Eagle]]\n* Founder and Grand Master of the [[Mexican Imperial Orders#Imperial Order of Saint Charles|Order of Saint Charles]]\n\n;Foreign<ref name=\"RoyalArk\"/><ref name = \"HofUndStaat\">[http://alex.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/alex?aid=shb&datum=1866&page=8&size=45  Hof- und Staats-Handbuch der \u00d6sterreichisch-Ungarischen Monarchie] (1866), Genealogy p. 2</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* {{flag|Austrian Empire}}:\n** [[Order of the Golden Fleece#Austrian Order|Knight of the Golden Fleece]], 1852<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antiquesatoz.com/sgfleece/knights5.htm |title=Chevaliers de la Tois\u00f3n d'Or - Knights of the Golden Fleece |last= Boettger|first=T. F.|date=|website=La Confr\u00e9rie Amicale|publisher=|access-date=25 June 2019|quote= }}</ref>\n** Grand Cross, [[Order of St. Stephen of Hungary]], 1856<ref>[http://tornai.com/rendtagok.htm \"A Szent Istv\u00e1n Rend tagjai\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222022855/http://tornai.com/rendtagok.htm|date=22 December 2010}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Baden}}: Knight, [[House Order of Fidelity]]\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Bavaria}}: [[Order of St. Hubert|Knight of St. Hubert]], 1856\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon (military), [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Royal Order of Leopold I]], 27 July 1857\n* {{flag|Empire of Brazil}}: Grand Cross, [[Order of the Southern Cross]]\n* {{flag|Brunswick}}: Grand Cross, [[Order of Henry the Lion]]\n* {{flag|Denmark}}: [[Order of the Elephant|Knight of the Elephant]], 11 January 1866<ref>{{cite book|author=J\u00f8rgen Pedersen|title=Riddere af Elefantordenen, 1559\u20132009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glw-AQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Syddansk Universitetsforlag|language=da|isbn=978-87-7674-434-2|p=273}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Second French Empire}}: Grand Cross, [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n* {{flagicon|Greece|royal}} [[Kingdom of Greece]]: Grand Cross, [[Order of the Redeemer]]\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Hanover}}:\n** [[Order of St. George (Hanover)|Knight of St. George]], 1856<ref>''Hof- und