{"title_page": "2012 Northern Territory general election", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2012 Northern Territory general election\n| country = Northern Territory\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2008 Northern Territory general election\n| previous_year = 2008\n| next_election = 2016 Northern Territory general election\n| next_year = 2016\n| seats_for_election = All 25 seats of the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]<br />13 seats were needed for a majority\n| election_date      = 25 August 2012\n\n<!--      Country Liberal Party     -->\n| image1 = [[File:Terry Mills (Australian Politician).png |120px]]\n| leader1 = [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]]\n| leader_since1 = 29 January 2008\n| party1 = Country Liberal Party\n| leaders_seat1 = [[Electoral division of Blain|Blain]]\n| popular_vote1 = '''46,653'''\n| percentage1 = '''55.8%'''  <ref name=\"ABC News\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/antonygreen/2012/09/northern-territory-election-updates.html|title=Antony Greens's Election Blog: Final Figures for 2012 Northern Territory Election|work=ABC News |date=2 September 2012 |accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref>\n| swing1 = {{increase}}5.1\n| last_election1  = 11 seats\n| seats_before1   = 12 seats\n| seats1 = '''16 seats'''\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}}4\n\n<!--      Labor      -->\n| image2 = [[File:No image.svg|140px]]\n| leader2 = [[Paul Henderson (politician)|Paul Henderson]]\n| leader_since2 = 26 November 2007\n| party2 = Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)\n| leaders_seat2 = [[Electoral division of Wanguri|Wanguri]]\n| popular_vote2 = 33,594\n| percentage2 = 44.2% <ref name=\"ABC News\"/>\n| swing2 = {{decrease}}5.1\n| last_election2  = 13 seats\n| seats_before2   = 12 seats\n| seats2 = 8 seats\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}}4\n\n| title = [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]]\n| posttitle = Elected Chief Minister\n| before_election = [[Paul Henderson (politician)|Paul Henderson]]\n| before_party = Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)\n| after_election = [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]]\n| after_party = Country Liberal Party\n| map_image       = Northern Territory general election, 2012.svg\n| map_size        = 350px\n| map_caption     = Results by electoral division.\n}}\n\nThe '''Northern Territory general election'''  was held on Saturday 25 August 2012, which elected all 25 members of the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] in the [[unicameral]] [[Northern Territory Parliament]]. The 11-year [[Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)|Labor Party]] government led by [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]] [[Paul Henderson (politician)|Paul Henderson]] was defeated in their attempt to win a fourth term against the opposition [[Country Liberal Party]] led by [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|opposition leader]] [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] with a swing of four seats, losing the normally safe Labor remote seats of [[Electoral division of Arafura|Arafura]], [[Electoral division of Arnhem|Arnhem]], [[Electoral division of Daly|Daly]] and [[Electoral division of Stuart|Stuart]], whilst retaining their urban seats picked up at the [[2001 Northern Territory general election|2001 election]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/elections/nt/2012/guide/sop.htm |title = State of the Parties - Northern Territory Votes 2012 - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-08-25/nt-votes-live-blog/4222578 |title = As it happened: NT votes 2012|date = 25 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{main|Results of the Northern Territory general election, 2012}}\n\n{{Australian elections/Title row\n| title        = Northern Territory general election, 25 August 2012<ref name=ntec-summary>[http://www.ntec.nt.gov.au/ElectionsAndReferendums/LegislativeAssemblyElections/PastLegislativeAssemblyElections/Pages/Legislative-Assembly-General-Election---25th-August-2012.aspx Legislative Assembly General Election - 25th August 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601092156/http://www.ntec.nt.gov.au/ElectionsAndReferendums/LegislativeAssemblyElections/PastLegislativeAssemblyElections/Pages/Legislative-Assembly-General-Election---25th-August-2012.aspx |date=1 June 2016 }}, Northern Territory Electoral Commission.</ref>\n| house        = [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]]\n| series       = Northern Territory general election\n| back         = 2008\n| forward      = 2016\n| enrolled     = 123,805\n| total_votes  = 95,215\n| turnout %    = 76.9\n| turnout chg  = +1.3\n| informal     = 3,072\n| informal %   = 3.2\n| informal chg = \u22120.9\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |government = yes\n  |party_id    = CLP\n  |votes       = 46,653\n  |votes %     = 50.6\n  |votes chg   = +5.2\n  |seats       = 16\n  |seats chg   = +5\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |party_id    = Labor NT\n  |votes       = 33,594\n  |votes %     = 36.5\n  |votes chg   = \u22126.7\n  |seats       = 8\n  |seats chg   = \u22125\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |party_id    = Greens NT\n  |votes       = 3,039\n  |votes %     = 3.3\n  |votes chg   = \u22121.0\n  |seats       = 0\n  |seats chg   = \u00b10\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |party_id    = First Nations\n  |votes       = 2,048\n  |votes %     = 2.2\n  |votes chg   = +2.2\n  |seats       = 0\n  |seats chg   = \u00b10\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |party_id    = Sex Party\n  |votes       = 717\n  |votes %     = 0.8\n  |votes chg   = +0.8\n  |seats       = 0\n  |seats chg   = \u00b10\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |party_id    = Independent\n  |votes       = 5,566\n  |votes %     = 6.0\n  |votes chg   = \u22121.1\n  |seats       = 1\n  |seats chg   = \u00b10\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Party summary|\n  |party_id    = Other\n  |votes       = 526\n  |votes %     = 0.6\n  |votes chg   = +0.6\n  |seats       = 0\n  |seats chg   = \u00b10\n}}\n{{Australian elections/Total row |\n  |total_votes = 92,143\n  |total_seats = 25\n}}\n{{Australian elections/2PP summary |\n  |party id 1  = CLP\n  |2pp votes 1 = 51,435\n  |2pp % 1     = 55.8\n  |2pp chg 1   = +5.1\n  |party id 2  = Labor NT\n  |2pp votes 2 = 40,709\n  |2pp % 2     = 44.2\n  |2pp chg 2   = \u22125.1\n}}\n|}\n\nIndependents: [[Gerry Wood]]\n\nTwo safe Labor seats were uncontested at the previous election and therefore did not contribute to votes and results, all seats were contested at this election with the two previously uncontested Labor seats both won by the CLP.\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Popular vote|titlebar=#ddd|width=600px|barwidth=410px|bars={{bar percent|Country Liberal|{{Country Liberal Party/meta/color}}|50.6}}\n{{bar percent|Labor|{{Australian Labor Party/meta/color}}|36.5}}\n{{bar percent|Greens|{{Australian Greens/meta/color}}|3.3}}\n{{bar percent|First Nations|#964B00|2.2}}\n{{bar percent|Sex Party|{{Australian Sex Party/meta/color}}|0.8}}\n{{bar percent|Independents|{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}}|6.0}}\n{{bar percent|Other|#777777|0.6}}}}\n\n{{bar box\n| title=Two-party-preferred vote\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|'''Country Liberal'''|{{Country Liberal Party/meta/color}}|55.8}}\n{{bar percent|Labor|{{Australian Labor Party/meta/color}}|44.2}}\n}}\n{{bar box\n|title=Seats|titlebar=#ddd|width=600px|barwidth=410px|bars={{bar percent|'''Country Liberal'''|{{Country Liberal Party/meta/color}}|64.0}}\n{{bar percent|Labor|{{Australian Labor Party/meta/color}}|32.0}}\n{{bar percent|Independents|{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}}|4.00}}}}\n\n== Background ==\nHistorically, remote areas had voted Labor while the urban areas had voted CLP. The CLP had governed since the [[1974 Northern Territory general election|initial 1974 election]] until Labor led by [[Clare Martin]] surprisingly came to power with a one-seat [[majority government]] at the [[2001 Northern Territory general election|2001 election]], mainly by sweeping Darwin's more diverse northern suburbs. Labor won in a landslide at the [[2005 Northern Territory general election|2005 election]], winning the second-largest majority in the Territory's history and reducing the CLP to only four seats. Although Labor led by Henderson retained a one-seat majority government at the [[2008 Northern Territory general election|2008 election]] on 13 Labor, 11 CLP, 1 independent with only 49.3 percent of the [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-party preferred]] vote, Labor had won two seats uncontested by the CLP\u2014all seats were contested again at the 2012 election. Labor, the CLP, the [[Northern Territory Greens]], the [[Australia's First Nations Political Party|First Nations Political Party]] and the [[Australian Sex Party]] were running endorsed candidates.\n\nA [[minority government]] was led by Henderson from mid-2009 when [[Alison Anderson]] resigned from the Labor Party to sit as an independent member of parliament. Anderson along with the existing independent [[Gerry Wood]] signed a letter to the speaker of parliament to push sittings forward, prompting CLP leader Mills to table a [[motion of no confidence]] on Monday 10 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2009/08/07/73421_ntnews.html |title=D-Day brought forward |work=Northern Territory News |date=7 August 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/08/07/2649483.htm |title=NT Labor may be ousted next week |publisher=ABC News |date=7 August 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/labors-fate-uncertain-20090810-efl9.html |title=Labor's fate uncertain |work=The Age |date=11 August 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> Wood ended up voting with the government, defeating the motion of no confidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25927928-5006790,00.html |title=Labor survives D-day in NT showdown |work=The Australian |date=14 August 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> Anderson joined the CLP in September 2011, resulting in 12 Labor, 12 CLP, 1 independent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2011/09/09/259011_ntnews.html |title=Anderson 'mates' with an old enemy |work=Northern Territory News |date=9 September 2011 |accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> Wood and Anderson retained their seats at the 2012 election.\n\nIn October 2010, former CLP leader [[Jodeen Carney]] resigned in her seat, an [[2010 Araluen by-election|Araluen by-election]] was held, the CLP retained the seat but suffered a 6.6-point [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-party preferred]] swing.\n\n== Method ==\nLike the [[Australian House of Representatives]], members were elected through full-preference [[instant-runoff voting]] in [[single-member electorates]]. The election was conducted by the Northern Territory Electoral Commission, an independent body answerable to Parliament.\n\nIn a change to polling in remote electorates, where most voting was previously conducted by mobile polling teams, for the first time there was full election day voting in major regional indigenous centres. As such, swings may be distorted. The conducting of a formal polling place could also alter the way voting takes places and increase the local turnout. Mobile polling teams were still used but they took many fewer votes than in the past. In addition, for the first time in the territory, there was an electronic feed of results, the last administration in Australia to go electronic.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/antonygreen/2012/08/2012-nt-election-how-to-follow-the-abc-coverage-on-saturday-night-.html |title = Antony Green|date = 11 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Date ==\nThe Henderson Labor government introduced fixed four-year terms following the previous election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/antonygreen/2009/08/fixed-term-parliaments-face-test-in-northern-territory.html |title=Fixed Term Parliaments face test in Northern Territory |publisher=ABC News |first=Antony |last=Green |authorlink=Antony Green |date=4 August 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Legislative Assembly was dissolved on 6 August 2012. The electoral roll was closed on 8 August and nominations on 10 August, prior to polling day on 25 August.<ref>{{cite web |first=Antony |last=Green |title=2012 Northern Territory Election Website now live |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=13 June 2012 |url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/antonygreen/2012/06/2012-northern-territory-election-website-now-live.html |accessdate=13 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe election was held on the same day as the [[2012 Heffron state by-election|Heffron state by-election]] in [[New South Wales]].\n\n== Retiring MPs ==\n\n=== Labor ===\n* [[Jane Aagaard]] ([[Electoral division of Nightcliff|Nightcliff]])\n* [[Chris Burns (politician)|Chris Burns]] ([[Electoral division of Johnston|Johnston]])\n* [[Marion Scrymgour]] ([[Electoral division of Arafura|Arafura]])\n\n== Candidates ==\n\nSitting members are in '''bold'''. Successful candidates are highlighted in the relevant colour.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border:1px solid #aaa; border-collapse:collapse\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Electorate\n! Held By\n! [[Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)|Labor]] Candidate\n! [[Country Liberal Party|CLP]] Candidate\n! [[Northern Territory Greens|Greens]] Candidate\n! Other Candidates\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n| || || {{Australian party style|Labor}}| ||{{Australian party style|CLP}}| ||{{Australian party style|Greens}} | || style=\"background:#